segments.text: The towns included New Boston, Clarksville, Allen, Texas, Woodway, then studies for a number of independent individuals not associated with some of the cities, and then for the city of Lakeside and the Fort Worth area, or Lake
I'm sorry, Lake Worth Village, which was at Lakeside.
And for the Lake Worth Independent School District planning study, that's a school district located at the north end of the approach into Carswell Air Force Base.
And so there was a certain amount of activity I had through the north Texas area
working on a contractual basis for some of these towns.
That was under the old 701 planning program.
Now, let's go back to the education area, and let me just comment a little bit.
The Federation of North Texas Area Universities consists of North Texas, East Texas, and Texas Women's University, as I already mentioned.
The program there is focused on merging together
in terms of degrees and hopefully course offerings, the delivery system, the whole combination of things, a unified, coordinated set of offerings in various fields.
Each field comes up before the Coordinating Board for its own independent approval.
The graduate program in adult continuing ed was approved
in 1974, April 74, to give authorization for the awarding of MA, MS, MED, PhD, and EDDs at all three of the institutions.
This was one of the programs.
Typically, some others included psychology.
They've included areas like early childhood studies.
They have included programs in, at one time, I believe, in chemistry and so forth.
Most of these have been within the area of education, but not totally.
There are, for instance, some in vocational technical training.
One of the things that we have striven for is to find ways within our ACED committee to bring together the scheduling of classes
and getting established common admission standards, getting a common core of courses, course descriptions that would be the same at all three institutions.
And of course, that means titles as well.
Getting examinations administered on a three university basis, rather than each one doing its own
under some sort of local departmental guideline.

We are aware within this group, in adult continuing ed, that we have quite presently a diversity of orientations to the handling of doctoral exams, ranging all the way from three-day written exams to one-day written exams.
North Texas, for instance, has a half-day proficiency exam in research tools.
We at East Texas rely on coursework to take care of those research proficiency tool requirements.
TWU has a different set of criteria.
They use core courses for examination along the way before the student ever gets admitted to doctoral exams.

We are attempting right now, and the adult continuing ed committee is very active presently and during this academic year of 85-86, with the support of the graduate deans, with the support of the vice presidents, with the support of the presidents of the three institutions, to move forward on unifying the entire approach.
The nearest program unifies its approach
Maybe there are two.
Early childhood for one in terms of the promotional aspects of the program and psychology from the standpoint of the course requirements and masters and doctoral examination requirements.
Those are perhaps the hallmarks of those two programs.
early childhood, for example.
I think planners need to be thinking in these terms.
That program has brought in specialists in the early childhood field.
And the programs that they have developed have been of interest to people from not only all over North Texas, the East Texas area, but generally across the state.
And folks will come in, even from Corpus Christi and other such points,
to hear these national and sometimes internationally known figures speaking on problems of early childhood.

I see the same potential application for the federation of the graduate schools of planning bringing in people of international stature because planners from all over the state of Texas and beyond the boundaries would be interested if those people were going to be here for or in Austin or wherever for a one-day seminar.
It could be very, very appealing, very attractive.

And, in fact, early childhood has made money on this, and they consistently have a kitty of $2,000 to $5,000 that they can use to promote their programs and to guarantee honorariums and so on and travel expenses and lodging and so on.
And that's a very good thing, I think, as a service to professionals in the state
And to my way of thinking, the planners in the state would be very interested in hearing individuals of international renown.
This would be non-state funds also.
That's right.
It's non-state funds.
So it's not subject to line item vetoes either, or budget funds.
You have complete freedom on what you spend it on as well.
Right.
Now the interesting thing is that our federation
has a certain amount of basic funding.

And the Federation, the Council of Presidents, as they are called, in turn, on recommendations of the graduate deans and the vice presidents, make decisions as to where small amounts of money should go to various programs.
It may be $200 or $500 or $700 or $800 for the year for a program committee, such as Adult Continuing Ed.
But early childhood.
has taken that money and they have spun off these programs, which have become enormously popular and successful.
And as a matter of fact, they turn around in some cases and even arrange for students to enroll in one hour courses.
Sometimes these seminars will be five day, full time, five day seminars.
And students can even enroll for credit or for continuing education units.
And of course, from the standpoint of a practicing professional in the planting field, the CEUs could be a way of encouraging them to come in.
Well, you know, the Educational Foundation is charged with the educational function of the chapter.
And the only real activity that they've undertaken continually is the short course for planning commissioners and elected public officials.
And there's always been talk of continuing education for degreed planners.
And this has never happened.
Well, this would be a place where

the institutions could, on a cooperative basis with the Education Foundation, come together and offer programs that would help the practicing professional and others who are skilled, whether they be in private practice or public practice.
Another thing that has always been talked about is getting together a unit that could be used throughout Texas in high school.

usually we're thinking lately about the junior year rather than the senior year, and have this available with a member of AICP to be there with the canned product, as it were, that would be in some media form, and to carry on a conversation and a discussion of it
Yeah, I think that should be done, especially because the high schools have their career days very regularly.
There are lots of them here in the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
And it's a very popular kind of event.
I think planning needs to be very much more concerned with recruiting high level.
entries into the profession.
Let me comment on one other aspect of that.
And this is something that I have touched on earlier.
But I think that the planning programs, in terms of the content of the curriculum, but more especially in the working arrangement, the programs need to be giving some serious consideration to it.

I have had opportunity to observe both those programs that are operated within and at the level of a single department program versus, on the other hand, those programs that are operated in a coordinated fashion embracing several departments.
There are weaknesses in the multidisciplinary approach from the standpoint of program control and management.
Those, though, in my judgment, can be overcome.
And people in continuing education have that same kind of problem.
I didn't get rid of those problems when I left.
The planning field actively moved over to education.
But I must say, candidly,

I see some serious weaknesses in the folks coming out of the graduate programs in planning in being so singular in focus, whether it be an urban design selectivity or an urban analysis selectivity or whatever you might want to name it, an administrative selectivity.
that they don't seem to have the inadequate understanding of the total dimension of the field.
I don't mean expertise in all these areas.
But they don't seem to have a good, solid understanding of the other side.
They do get some theoretical exposure, as I see it in most of these programs, but some understanding of the working tools in the other disciplines.
For example,

and not challenging the program at A&M, but simply pointing out by way of asking the question, do the students in the graduate program at A&M get an exposure to population statistics and the analysis of demographic data from a statistical point of view that a demographer will say, yes, that person's on the right track.

do they get that same exposure to public administration case analysis whereby the person who is a practicing public administrator with a background in public administration will be able to say, yes, that person has correctly approached the analysis of these case studies.
That's the kind of thing I'm talking about.
Would the geographer, the experienced qualified geographer, be able to say,
yes, the procedures that are being followed in the analysis of the geographic implications have been correctly addressed.

The theoretical base is important, but I think the thing that I find so often missing is that the student doesn't really appreciate exactly what it is the person in the other field is expecting from a performance standpoint.
It's not the lack of theoretical base,
It's the understanding of how the geographer should work in the situation.
There is professional methodologies.
Yes, it's the professional methodologies with kind of a fundamental understanding of the underlying theory, but not totally absorbed by the underlying theory.
Flabel Shurtleff, years ago, when he was very active in AIP,

gave a talk at Long Beach, which I remember very well, sitting in a room of about 35 or 40 people and listening to him expound on the problems that he had done, kind of a joint effort at MIT and Harvard, talking of .
You were in Long Beach.
OK.
In that Long Beach session.

He presented the results of a study that had been done reaching across both academic and practitioner lines, trying to identify courses and content areas that individuals felt a graduate program in planning should have under the belt before going into private practice.
And he said, we eliminated
not only the duplications, but also those various areas that seemed to be rather minuscule.
And he said, we then put semester hours or quarter hours credits on it, added it all up.
And he said, for a person who would enter a graduate program in planning, say, at age 22 or 23, maybe with a couple of years experience under the belt, maybe age 25 or 26,
He said, we found that the person would be 72 years old if they took all the required courses.
Beautiful.
Beautiful, yeah.
I'm not surprised.
Well, obviously, this is a horrendous problem.
I guess my plea is that the people have some understanding of, as you put it, the methodologies that give the planner
recognition by counterparts in the other fields that they are connected with.
It's not that they know all of the nitty gritty details, but that their methodological approaches sound.
Because that's the thing I have found consistently so often.
For instance, people coming out of urban design programs, relatively little understanding of how the geographer works, how the sociologist works.
Almost no understanding of communication skills.
And this is terrible.
Probably the greatest weaknesses in that area.
And certainly no understanding of how final decisions are made.
No, no.
The political process is just... Out to lunch.
Gone.
Totally gone.
And a lot of them stumble and fall because of that.
Or they get frustrated with it.
And there's no reason for that.
They need to recognize the process.
Kent kept homing in on process in his writings about how you have to do this and this and this.
And I think it's a point that you have to be constantly aware of.
Planning is not something done in a vacuum.
It's got to be done with the people.
How do you feel that the three recognized schools should relate to each other in Texas?

My feeling would be that they ought to put together a united front as a consortium, a consortium of planning schools, or I should use that instead of federation, because I think it might make a stronger approach that
One, there would be first an acceptance of certain core courses, especially that first year of graduate study.
And then second, that there would be, because of the core, those core courses with common agreement on substance, content, description, would then be transferable from one institution to the other.
But beyond that, that there would then also be agreement
leadership provided by all three schools in furnishing work experience, on-site experience in various locales in the state.
And I don't care where it is.
That would be up to the institution and the student needs.
But I think beyond that, it would be very helpful if in the final review of students,

probably the end of the third semester of their graduate study, that there could be an evaluation step, maybe near the end of that third semester or just before they go into the fourth, an evaluation step where faculty from all three institutions would come together and review the work of all of those third semester students and say, here are the strengths, here are the weaknesses,
this student needs to get some special attention, not necessarily another course.
But in that fourth semester, hone in on this particular area.
Mike at A&M, I recognize the need for some kind of review of the student's work prior to the final oral exam.
Right.
That's what I'm talking about.
And so I instituted the midpoint review.

The midpoint review is not intended as an exam, but as a review of the student's work and to try to take a look at anything that needed bolstering up during the last half of his or her academic career, and also a chance for the student to voice any aspirations for the department, anything that might
have been hoped for that didn't come to fruition, wasn't realized, that would help the department.
And of course, that's a very difficult thing for the student to do, because they're still there and they're still being graded.
But I understand what you're saying.
But on the basis of a consortium of three institutions that would make that a bit more meaningful,
I think it would from the standpoint that these people are not going to continue to work in College Station or Ryan.
And therefore, they're going to be competing with graduates from the other institutions in San Antonio, in Houston, in Corpus, Dallas, Fort Worth, and other points.
Also, it would make it very much more of a professional type of review.
Yes.
And that's what my concern is, that it not be an academic grading process
it not be the jury, but rather it be a professional relationship between individuals in the institutions almost representing the role of prospective employers and the students as prospective workers.
And therefore, bringing those two together in that context

so that the student would be able to say at the end of the program, collectively, in the wisdom of the faculty in the three institutions, I have done what they said I needed to do in order to be ready for the field.
The only thing I would add to this is that I think there must be somebody from a practicing professional, maybe from a private
operation and someone from a public operation sit in on that consortium review of those students.

I feel that's essential in order to be sure that because of the mix of faculty maybe in that review process, things don't get warped one way or another and get out of context with what goes on in practice.
That's why we have a representative of the graduate college on our PhD committee.
Right.
Sure.
just to ensure fairness.
Right.
This reminds me of the relationship in planning between Harvard and MIT, where one can take courses at either institution for credit.
Right.
And if they can do it, I can see no reason why we in our own state under one coordinating board for higher education couldn't accomplish it.
Right.
And I think the coordinating board would be the vehicle to accomplish a consortium.
Yeah.
To me, it's the logical thing.
It would mean that the deans of the schools or the graduate deans, perhaps more specifically, and the VPs and presidents could really be the parent body.
Well, I think it might be very realistic to think in these terms right now with the budget crunch.
Yes.
And you see, that's what has happened with the adult continuing ed program.
And that is, although the budget crunch hadn't
surfaced as visible.
It was 1 tenth of the tip of the iceberg that was shown.
But everybody was aware that something could happen.
We were already under constraints in the three schools about hiring additional people.
Now we're at the constraint of don't hire replacements.
We were really feeling, and I say this from the standpoint of faculty

and had felt for a number of years a desire to get together, what we are now finding is that we now have the attention of the vice presidents and the presidents who are saying, uh-oh, we better find a way to maximize the capabilities of the faculties in these three institutions.
And mind you, we're only talking about myself full time.

and a part-time faculty member at East Texas, one full-time person at TW who will be leaving at the end of this year, and one other full-time and a couple of part-time people maybe doing one course per semester in the area, and only one at North Texas.
So we're talking only about a very few faculty.
Yeah.
Paragraph.
Mike, would you care to comment on the Kessler
contribution to the planning of Fort Worth?
Interestingly, when I was there as planning director, we dug out some of the old material from the Kessler studies, the Kessler planning work.
I found very little, very little knowledge of Kessler ever having done work in Fort Worth by the man or woman on the street.
That was unlike the situation in El Paso, where I talked with a great many people who remembered Kessler as a very dynamic individual.
He came in.
He was involved.
He talked with local groups.
In fact, I had people tell me that they remembered 25 years earlier having gone to a public meeting where Kessler spoke.
I never encountered that in Fort Worth.
I don't know why, whether I just didn't bump into the right people, did not meet them, maybe they were gone.
Herman Cox, who was the chairman of the Planning Commission when I went to Fort Worth, may have had some contact with Kessler years before.
But seemingly, the impression was just very nil.
And we resuscitated part of his work for an exhibit
that we put on in Fort Worth.
Where that material is today, I do not know.
We had also done a study.

In fact, a review of the Kessler material was prompted in part because shortly after I went there, we were doing a study on trying to find some way to bring the four railroads together into common terminal facilities and so on.
It did not meet with success.
One of them, MoTak, turned around deliberately and started to enlarge their own facility so they wouldn't get trapped into doing something with the Santa Fe.
At least that's my assessment of it.
They expanded in any case.
Mike, this may take the record as the longest interview.
I'm afraid so.
We covered a lot of cities in the process and a lot of topics.
And I want to thank you for your time and your contribution
of the Texas chapter of APA.
Quite welcome.
And this closes out the interview.
If I could ever do anything with the foundation, I'd be glad to do it.
And if there's anything on promotion of the programs in the state for continuing into the planners, I'd certainly be welcome.
Look upon that as a very welcome opportunity.
Thank you.
